ed volume, which includes images by famed photographers Ansel Adams and Galen Rowell, describes the natural and human histories of the system's many reserves. Located throughout California, these wildland habitats range from coastal tide pools to inland deserts, from lush wetlands to ancient forests, and from vernal pools to oak savannas. By supporting teaching, research, and public service within such protected landscapes, the UC NRS contributes to the understanding and wise stewardship of the Earth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEcologyxStudy and teachingxCalifornia. 0aEnvironmental protectionxCalifornia. 0aNatural areasxCalifornia. 0aNatural historyxStudy and teachingxCalifornia. 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh1 aFiedler, Peggy L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRumsey, Susan Gee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWong, Kathleen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520953642423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520953642.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles